Observation Details: Goat farm at trailhead.
First seen flying over, then circles back and landed at top of spruce.
First thought they were robins in flight, then as they got closer the flight pattern and tail shape revealed them as PIGR. Landed in talk trees next to VTC, likely staging to raid nearby ornamentals.

Large flock moving frequently, foraging in weedy field then flying in circles before settling back down. Counted 10, then multiplied to estimate 50. Estimated 7 multiples of 50. One exceedingly pale bird, likely the “angel” Common Redpoll photographed by others at this site.

Estimate by tens than fifties of large, constantly moving flock. I’ll add and attempt to count from photos. Searched carefully for HORE, though neither of the two paler birds I noticed were seen well enough to rule out CORE. Flushed by the arrival of the RTHA; flock flew west over treeline beyond the farm.

Location: Norman and Selma Greenberg Conservation Reserve
Norman and Selma Greenberg Conservation Reserve

Observation Details: Exact count of 17. I was standing in my grandparents driveway, working on my car at dusk. I heard some NOCA chip notes, and looked up to see 4 NOCA fly out of a nearby cedar and around the back of the house. Within a few second there was a flurry of other chip notes, and over the course of a minute I counted 13 more NOCA fly into the cedar from across the field to the south. My guess is that they are roosting in the cedar stand in back of the house at night and then dispersing to nearby feeders and thickets during the day. It was an excited moment, and the most NOCA I've ever seen at one time.
